Data Analysis Project: Find the Area to Invest

Xueqing Xie

Introduction

Goal:

A real estate company has a niche in purchasing properties with two-bedroom to rent out short-term as part of their business model specifically within New York City. They want to have a data product with a rational conclusion to help them find out what are the zip codes that will generate the most profit on short term rentals within New York City.

Datasets:

Cost data: Zillow provides us an estimation of value for two-bedroom properties

Revenue data: AirBnB is the medium through which the investor plans to lease out their investment property.

Basic Assumptions:

The investor will pay for the property in cash (i.e. no mortgage/interest rate will need to be accounted for).

The time value of money discount rate is 0% (i.e. $1 today is worth the same 100 years from now).

All properties and all square feet within each locale can be assumed to be homogeneous (i.e. a 1000 square foot property in a locale such as Bronx or Manhattan generates twice the revenue and costs twice as much as any other 500 square foot property within that same locale.)

Additional Assumption:

  1. Rent is the only revenue for the property; cost contains the property purchasing cost and the operating expenses.

  2. Operating expenses are 50% of revenue (salary, marketing, devices…) and the occupancy rate is 75%.

  3. The properties are available throughout a year (365 days).

  4. The investor will not sell the property in the period we investigate.

  5. The rental price keeps constant in the period we investigate (from 2017 to 2019+).

  6. The company has adequate cash to purchase ideal properties.

  7. The investment will happen in 2017.

  8. The property type makes no difference.

The whole process will be:

Data Overview: know the size of data, the basic variables and their relationship.

Data Quality Check: check the fraud data, missing value, inconsistent data format, outliers, etc.

Data Cleaning : Solve the problem found in data quality check and clean the data.

Data Analysis : Create new features helpful to analyze the problem, visualize data, make conclusion and recommendation and think about the future work to improve the current work.

Data Cleaning

Summary of data cleaning

(1) Airbnb Dataset:

Zipcode:
Filter zipcodes with 5 digits
Remove missing value

Price:
Remove dollar sign and comma in price Change the data type to numeric type

Others:
Filter “is_location_exact” which is true
Remove outliers in every borough

(2) Zillow Dataset:

Zipcode:
Filter zipcodes with 5 digits
Rename the column name from RegionName to zipcode
Filter the zipcode in New York

Price:
Make sure no missing value
Use the mean of lastest three month as purchasing price

Airbnb Dataset

#Outlier function (extreme outliers)
is_outlier <- function(x) {
  return(x < quantile(x, 0.25) - 3 * IQR(x) |
  x > quantile(x, 0.75) + 3 * IQR(x))
}

#Clean data (data type, filter, remove outliers)
airbnb_final <- airbnb2 %>%
  mutate(price = as.numeric(gsub(",", "", (
  gsub("\\$", "", price)
  )))) %>%
  filter(is_location_exact == "t" &
  !is.na(zipcode) & (str_length(zipcode)) == 5) %>%
  group_by(neighbourhood_group_cleansed) %>%
  mutate(outlier = is_outlier(price)) %>%
  filter(outlier == FALSE) %>%
  select(c(1, 2, 4, 5, 8, 9))

airbnb_final %>% ggplot(aes(x = neighbourhood_group_cleansed, y = price, fill =
                              neighbourhood_group_cleansed)) +

New Feature

Fomula

\[Expected Revenue/year= DailyRent * Days/year* Occupancy Rate\]

\[Return On Investment= (ExpectedRevenue/year-OperatingExpense/year)/TotalCost\]

\[BreakEvenPeriod=TotalCost/(ExpectedRevenue/year-OperatingExpense/year))\]

Create new features

After creating new features and grouping data by zipcode, we finally keep 24 zipcodes in our dataset to do final analysis. 

data2 <- data %>%
  group_by(zipcode) %>%
  summarise(
  mean_rent_price = mean(price),
  mean_reviews = mean(number_of_reviews),
  purchase_price = mean(purchase_price),
  neighbourhood = first(neighbourhood_group_cleansed),
  SizeRank = first(SizeRank),
  City = first(City)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
  occupancy_rate = 0.75,
  revenue_y01 = mean_rent_price * 365 * 0.75,
  return_rate = (revenue_y01 - 0.5 * revenue_y01) / purchase_price,
  break_even = purchase_price / (revenue_y01 - 0.5 * revenue_y01),
  country = "US"
  )

==================================================================================================================

Analysis and Conclusion

Summary:

  1. Although Queens and Staten Island have highest return ratios and shortest breakeven periods, the volume of potential customers(travelers) is much less than that of Manhattan and Brooklyn.

  2. Although Manhattan has highest cost in properties, and much higher break-even period than other places but there are still some place worth to invest. The price of real estate is more likely to increase and higher populations density means large potential market.

Recommendation:

I would recommend place with zipcode of 10025, 10036 in Manhattan and 11234 in Brooklyn. The portfolio with investment in different types of area can spread investment risks. The other reason is as follows:

Population scale: 10025 has a top population size rank compared to other zipcodes and 11234 in Brooklyn also has a great rank of population, while 10036 has a middle size of population, which is not bad to see a market potential.

Break-even point: Break-even point means the years it takes to start to earn a profit. These three places are in top-10 in terms of average break-even period. Zipcode 10025 and 10036 have the shortest break-even period of around 40 years in Manhattan and 11234 also has the shortest break-even period in Brooklyn of around 22 years, performing much better than other zipcodes in the same neighbourhood.

Return on investment: Opposite to break-even period, zipcode 10025 and 10036 have the highest annual return rate of over 2% in Manhattan and 11234 has the top annual return rate in Brooklyn of over 4%.

Cash liquity: Zipcode 10025 and 10036 are almost the cheapest region in Mahattan and they get a high annual revenue. 11234 in Brooklyn also take a cheap cost to buy. 11234 has a top population rank and thus we expect the rent prices in the area would increase in the future. With a appropriate cost to buy the property, the company could better control the budget on this investment with good revenue every year.

Social effect: The number of reviews of these places are between the middle and high level, which means people are more willing to live there and pay more attention to these area on social media than in many other places in NYC. Zipcode 11234 has a large volume of reviews, which means this area owns a good exposure in social media.
